solution.p:
A rough calculation shows that all ice melts and the temperature of the mixture will be more than 0^{\circ}C.  Let T be the temperature at the equilibrium.  Then, the equation balancing the energy gained to energy lost gives.

	 \amp  0.1\ \text{kg} \left(   2000\ \text{J/kg.C} \times 10^{\circ}\text{C} +  334,000 \ \text{J/kg} + 4186\ \text{J/kg.C} \times T \right)
	 \amp \ \ =  ( 0.5\ \text{kg} \times 4186\ \text{J/kg.C}  + 
	            0.4\ \text{kg} \times 837\ \text{J/kg.C} )\times
	             ( 60 - T).

Solving this equation we find T = 38.7^{\circ}C.  Therefore, the change of state can be described as

	 \amp \text{Initial State: }
	 \amp  \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \text{1. 0.1 kg ice at -10}^{\circ}\text{C}
	 \amp  \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \text{2. 0.5 kg of water at 60}^{\circ}\text{C}
	 \amp  \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \text{3. 0.4 kg of glass at 60}^{\circ}\text{C}


	 \amp \text{Final State: }
	 \amp  \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \text{1. 0.1 kg water at 38.7}^{\circ}\text{C}
	 \amp  \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \text{2. 0.5 kg of water at 38.7}^{\circ}\text{C}
	 \amp  \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \text{3. 0.4 kg of glass at 38.7}^{\circ}\text{C}
